{"cursor":"2847","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Milt Bernhart' (May 25, 1926 in Valparaiso, Indiana â January 22, 2004 in\nGlendale, California) was a West Coast jazz trombonist who worked with Stan\nKenton, Frank Sinatra, and others. He supplied the exciting solo heard in the\nmiddle of Sinatra's popular 1956 recording of [[I've Got You Under My\nSkin]], [http://www.tomsmithbigband.com/swing-music-\nhistory.html \"Swing Music History\"], last accessed Jan 12, 2010 conducted\nby Nelson Riddle.\n\nBernhart (occasionally spelled Bernhardt) began on tuba, but switched to\ntrombone in high school. At 16 he worked in Boyd Raeburn's band and later had\nsome \"gigs\" with Teddy Powell. After time in the United States Army he worked,\noff and on, with Stan Kenton for the next ten years. He is perhaps most\nassociated with Kenton, but in 1955 he had his first album as a leader. In 1986\nhe was elected President of the Big Band Academy of\nAmerica. [http://www.jazzhouse.org/gone/lastpost2.php3?edit=1074815283 Jazz\nHouse obituary]\n\nAlthough known as \"mild-mannered\" or humorous his brief period with Benny\nGoodman was one area that brought out his ire. He indicates working with Goodman\nwas \"the bottom\", except for basic training in the Army, of his first 23 years\nof life. He called Goodman a \"bore\" and claimed he did nothing about the\ntreatment Wardell Gray faced at a segregated club in Las Vegas. He even alleges\nthat he quit because Goodman publicly humiliated Gray in front of an\naudience. [http://www.jazzprofessional.com/humour/bernhart.htm Jazz\nProfessional Interview with Milt Bernhart]\n","linknr":124,"url":"Milt_Bernhart","recorded":1375067349,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Milt_Bernhart&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Milt_Bernhart&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentCh